Subject: Re: [T2] Power Bleeder

At 07:48 PM 06/09/2004, you wrote:
>  most power bleeders and pot
>style bleeders use compressed air and that forces moisture and
>contamination into the fluid.  not to mention that when dealing with shops
>they like to leave fluid in the bleeding pot which lets it soak up ambient
>moisture.

You are sadly misinformed. These commercial pressure bleeders have two 
chambers separated by a rubber bladder. You fill them with fluid then purge 
the fluid chamber of all air. The fluid is sealed off and cannot absorb 
humidity. The fluid stays fresh indefinately.
